# Q-SYS Lua — simple architecture

Use this for **small-to-medium** control scripts where a **flat, readable layout** matters more than shared utilities or a strict local-module shell.

**Reference scripts** (same section order and banner style):

- [`Funtional code (Archive)/-- Room Controls (Hope Roth (Original)).lua`](Funtional%20code%20(Archive)/--%20Room%20Controls%20(Hope%20Roth%20(Original)).lua)
- [`Running On Site/GFL/ClockAudioController(Refactor).lua`](Running%20On%20Site/GFL/ClockAudioController(Refactor).lua)

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Header[Header comment]
    Config[Configuration]
    Tables[Constant Tables]
    Const[Constants]
    Funcs[Functions by domain banner]
    EH[Event Handlers]
    Init[Always Run / funcInit]
    Header --> Config --> Tables --> Const --> Funcs --> EH --> Init
```

## Section order

1. **Header comment** — script name, author/org, date, firmware requirement, version, one-line purpose.
2. **Configuration** — **first editable block after the header.** Site- and design-specific values that change when plugins, hardware, or naming change. See [Configuration block](#configuration-block) below.
3. **Constant tables** — runtime collections and component refs initialized empty or `nil` (e.g. `compMicBoxes = {}`, `compInvalid = {}`, `compCallSync = nil`).
4. **Constants** — toggles, UI strings, state flags, timer instances (`Timer.New()`).
5. **Functions** — one block opened by a top banner; **domain sub-banners** inside (Setup, Status, Discovery, feature areas, Components). Order callees before callers where practical.
6. **Event handlers** — assign `.EventHandler` on `Controls.*`, timers, and indexed control arrays **at file scope** (no required `registerEvents()` wrapper).
7. **Always run** — single `funcInit()` that fills choices, binds components, syncs feedback, then `funcInit()` called once at the bottom.

## Comment banners

Use the **bracket style** consistently:

```lua
-------------------[ Configuration ]-------------------
-------------------[ Constant Tables ]-------------------
-------------------[ Constants ]-------------------
-------------------[ Functions ]-------------------
-------------------[ Setup ]-------------------
-------------------[ Status ]-------------------
-------------------[ Event Handlers ]-------------------
-------------------[ Always Run ]-------------------
```

- **Top-level sections** use the full bracket banner above.
- **Function sub-areas** use the same bracket style with a domain label (Setup, Status, Discovery, Motion, Volume, Components, etc.) so jumps in a long file stay obvious.

## Configuration block

Put everything a technician might edit when deploying to a new room **immediately after the header**, before constant tables:

```lua
-------------------[ Configuration ]-------------------

local componentTypes = {
  callSync     = "call_sync",
  micBoxes     = "%PLUGIN%_91b57fdec7bd41fb9b9741210ad2a1f3_%FP%_6bb184f66fd3a12efe1844e433fc11c3",
  micMixer     = "mixer",
  roomControls = "device_controller_script",
}

-- optional name filter when type alone is not enough (inline in getComponentNames is also fine)
-- local roomControlsNameMatch = "^compRoomControls"

-- site/hardware maps (button indices, channel maps, timeouts, etc.)
micButtonConfigs = {
  {box = 1, buttons = {{6,1,1}, {8,2,2}, {10,3,3}}},
  -- ...
}
```

**Belongs in Configuration:**

- `local componentTypes` — Q-SYS `comp.Type` strings and plugin fingerprints; discovery loops reference `componentTypes.*` instead of repeating type strings.
- Per-site tables (button maps, I/O indices, channel routes, combo choice lists such as `MotionChoices`).
- Optional name-filter patterns when type alone is not enough.

**Does not belong in Configuration** (keep below):

- Runtime component refs (`compMicBoxes`, `compCallSync`) → **Constant tables**
- Debug toggles, `strClear`, timers, mutable state flags → **Constants**

In `getComponentNames()` (or equivalent):

```lua
if comp.Type == componentTypes.callSync then
  -- ...
elseif comp.Type == componentTypes.micBoxes then
  -- ...
elseif comp.Type == componentTypes.roomControls and string.match(comp.Name, "^compRoomControls") then
  -- ...
end
```

Use a small helper (e.g. `fillChoices`) inside discovery when many combo boxes share the same sort/clear/auto-select logic.

## Skeleton

```lua
--[[
  ScriptName - Q-SYS Control Script
  Author: ...
  Date: ...
  Version: ...
  Firmware Req: ...

  One-line purpose.

]]--

-------------------[ Configuration ]-------------------

local componentTypes = { ... }
-- site-specific tables here

-------------------[ Constant Tables ]-------------------

compInvalid = {}
-- compX = nil refs

-------------------[ Constants ]-------------------

stateDebug = false
strClear = "[Clear]"
timerExample = Timer.New()

-------------------[ Functions ]-------------------

-------------------[ Setup ]-------------------

function debugMsg(str) ... end

-------------------[ Status ]-------------------

function getStatus() ... end
function setComp(ctl, componentType) ... end

-------------------[ Discovery ]-------------------

function getComponentNames() ... end

-------------------[ Components ]-------------------

function setcompExample() ... end

-------------------[ Event Handlers ]-------------------

Controls.compExample.EventHandler = setcompExample

-------------------[ Always Run ]-------------------

function funcInit()
  getComponentNames()
  setcompExample()
end

funcInit()
```

## Patterns to follow

- **Direct `Controls.*`** in functions and handlers is fine; a `local controls = {}` map is optional.
- **Global `function Name()`** is the default for this style; `local function` is fine for small inner helpers only.
- **Component glue** — central helpers keep feature code short: `getComponentNames`, `setComp`, `getStatus`, `setCompValid` / `setCompInvalid`. Mirror the reference scripts, not necessarily the full-rule `setComponent` template.
- **Debug** — single gated `debugMsg` when `stateDebug` is true; optional room-prefixed console output is fine.
- **Init mirrors handlers** — `funcInit()` calls the same `setcomp*` paths that combo-box `.EventHandler` assignments use, plus `getComponentNames()` and any one-time sync (e.g. `syncLEDStates()`).
- **Guard optional controls** — wrap indexed or optional UI controls with `if Controls.compMicBox then ... end` before binding.

## Minimal code-quality rules

- **No OOP** — no `setmetatable`, `__index`, `.new()`, or `self` for controllers; one script context, one `Controls` surface.
- **Flat control flow** — guard clauses and early `return` over deep nesting.
- **Naming** — descriptive names; Q-SYS prefixes (`btn`, `txt`, `ctl`, `comp`) are normal. Loop iterators `i` / `j` / `v` are acceptable.

## Not required here (use the full rule instead)

For [`.cursor/rules/qsys-lua-architecture.mdc`](.cursor/rules/qsys-lua-architecture.mdc) patterns, treat these as **optional** unless you explicitly need them:

- Mandatory **`setProp` / `bind` / `bindArray` / `cleanupComponentHandlers`** toolkit.
- Fixed **local-module section order** and all **`local function`** at top level.
- **Complexity tiers**, dense refactoring checklists, and line-reduction targets.
- **Required `pcall` startup** — add only to surface init failures to `txtStatus` or the console.
- **`GlobalName = { ... }` public API** — only when another script must call into this file.

When a script grows (many rebinding selectors, cross-script APIs, or strict feedback-loop safety), migrate toward the full architecture rule rather than stretching this layout.
